This is a very good workout, especially if you are under 50 years of age. For us much older women, I recommend doing the workout but not as fast. And if there are any particular drills that hurt your knees, back, arms, neck, etc., then simply modify them. I taught martial arts and cardio boxing for years and had many women above 70 years of age who never thought they'd be able to get through the class, but I helped them modify the drills to suit their abilities. After 3 months, they were able to do the full drills, keeping up with me. It takes time if you are older, but keept it up. This is definitely a good workout for the entire body.

Okay, I've struggled so hard to find workouts on YouTube that would inspire me to exercise every day and push through my laziness, but *I love this*. First time has been quite exhausting, but the cool-down at the end? Totally worth it. I read in the comments that so many people benefitted from this one, so I'll definitely keep trying to do this every other day!

Update from Day 2: Today I had soared muscles from the same workout yesterday, so rounds 2 and 3 were about to break my spirit. I had to take some rest in between because of how short of breath I was, but managed to pull it together and keep on exercising. Today I slowed down some of the last combinations because I really wanted to feel the power in my kicks and control more of my abysmally weak abs and I hope it was effective. Cooldown was much needed and appreciated, as always. (Didn't manage to look at myself in the mirror because of how fat I look, tho).

Update from Day 3: Today has been quite tough, even though I managed to get through Rounds 2 and 3 without taking any rest. My goal for today was really trying to control breath during exercises. However, at the end I've started to feel out of energy, most probably because I also took 20 minutes of spinning. I know it sounds as if I'm asking too much from my body but I ate way too much at dinner and felt completely busted, so I had to workout a little bit more than usual. Have I already said that I love the cooldown?

Update from Day 5: Done!

Update from Day 6: Today I had my boyfriend do this workout with me and it was actually super fun to share this with someone. We both were exhausted but we managed to come through it!

Update from Day 7: Today I didn't feel like it and only managed to get through Round 2, and only with a great deal of self-control because all of my body feels so tired right now. It's not even painful, it's just completely exhausting. I tried to fight through Round 3 but the first uppercut made me realize that I couldn't make it, not today. I know I shouldn't go that easy on myself, since I'm so lazy all the time, but today's not it.

Know how I stayed motivated until getting up at 5:00 am to work out became a healthy habit?  I got a 3 ring binder and dividers, subscribed to a fitness magazine and would cut out articles.  I had a section for exercises, recipes, work-out log, diet log.  It was my "fitness bible".  I looked at it every day and it kept me motivated.  90% of this is in your head - after that you get to enjoy all the benefits of living a healthy lifestyle.  Start with long-term and short-term goals and break them down.  If you feel yourself getting burned out, change up your routine.  Best of luck!!
